{
  "texts": [
    "To define CopySwap, let |k⟩ be an m-qubit computational basis state, written in binary as k m-1 k m-2... k 0, so that k 0 represents the least significant bit.",
    "Let |ξ⟩ be an arbitrary single-qubit state.",
    "The operation CopySwap enacts the isometry from an m + 1 qubit state to a 2M -1 qubit spaceCopySwap (|k⟩ |ξ⟩) = |k m-1 ⟩ ⊗2 m-1 |k m-2 ⟩ ⊗2 m-2... |k 1 ⟩ ⊗2 |k 0 ⟩ |0 k ⟩ |ξ⟩ |0 M -k-1 ⟩(35)for any m-qubit computational basis state |k⟩ and any arbitrary single-qubit state |ξ⟩.",
    "Implementing CopySwap efficiently will involve a combination of copying layers and layers of parallel CSWAPs, depicted in Fig. 18 using the t and CS t subroutines defined in App.",
    "Similar to previous sections, the goal of performing many t operations before the corresponding CS t sequences at the earliest time is to ensure the CS t sequences can be maximally parallelized under 1 step.m m M -m-1 M -1 |k⟩ Copy |k m-1 ⟩ ⊗2 m-1... |k 0 ⟩ |ξ⟩ Swap |0 k ⟩ |ξ⟩ |0 M -k-1 ⟩ 2 48 16 2 4 8 2 4 2 2 2 2 2 2 4 4 4 4 8 8 8 16 16 R 4 0 1 3 4 Algorithm 7 Copy Swap Operation 1: procedure CopySwap Subroutine(R, S, m) ▷ m is the number of control bits ▷ R = R 0,...,R m-1 is the control register, where R j has size max(1, 2 m-j-2) ▷ S is the target register of size 2 m 2: for i in range(m) do ▷ O(m) 3: for j in range(1, mi) do ▷ All values of j performed in parallel with the CS operation 4: i (R j) 5: end for 6:C 4 R 3 0 1 3 C 3 R 2 0 1 C 2 R 1 0 C 1 R 0 C 0 S 0 S 1 S 2 S 3 S 4 |0⟩ |0 2 ⟩ S |0 4 ⟩ |0 8 ⟩ |0 16 ⟩CS i (R i, S) A.7 LOADFThe LOADF circuit is perhaps the key to making the whole protocol work."
  ]
